Ogun state governor, Prince Dapo Abiodun, former President Olusegun Obasanjo as well as the state chapter of All Progressives Congress (APC) have commiserated with President Muhammadu Buhari over the death of his Chief of Staff, Mallam Abba Kyari who passed on over Friday night.  While the duo of Ogun APC and governor Abiodun described Kyari’s death as a national tragedy that saddened hearts of the entire executive members of his administration, Obasanjo expressed sadness that the former Chief of Staff still lost the battle against COVID-19 despite his commitment and service to his fatherland.  In a letter of condolence addressed to President Buhari and personally signed by him, the former president noted that Kyari’s death would no doubt, be painful to him, family and other friends, but urged the President to take solace in the fact that his former Chief of Staff died in harness and service to Nigeria.  Praying God to grant Buhari and other family members, the fortitude to bear the “irreparable loss”, Obasanjo however advocated that Nigerians must collectively use Kyari’s death towards arriving at a common ground that will put Nigeria in good stead to successfully overcome the COVID-19 pandemic.  “His death must be a solemn reminder to all of us that COVID-19 requires all hands on deck soberly, cooperatively, humanly, humanely, justly, equitably, fairly, consolidated and comprehensively to be able to fight it successfully and to get all Nigerians back to good health and healthy economy”.  In his own condolence message, Ogun governor said COVID-I9 has “claimed its biggest victim”, stressing that the late CoS was “a detribalised Nigerian, consummate technocrat, gentleman and leading member of President Muhammadu Buhari’s team, for whom we had a lot respect”.  Recalling that late Abba Kyari carried out his duties with lots of charisma and high intellectual disposition, Abiodun said he would forever, remember late Abba Kyari as a great democrat, “a thoroughbred administrator, a good party man, a diligent networker and servant leader, whose service orientation could have helped Nigeria to tame the dreaded COVID-19”.  Ogun governor asserted that the late Chief of Staff would have helped Nigeria in finding solutions to COVID-19 pandemic, saying that Kyari’s passing wa a major blow “not only to the Buhari presidency but to all of us serving Nigeria at this critical period in our history”. 